# data-models

Two primary data models drive the core business functionality:

## Meeting Model
Importance Score: 90/100

Key Attributes:
- Structured signal extraction categories (decisions, action items, blockers, risks)
- Temporal state tracking (scheduled, in-progress, completed)
- Screenshot integration for visual context
- Multi-source transcript handling (Pocket, Teams)
- Signal merging capabilities with versioning

## Document Model  
Importance Score: 85/100

Key Attributes:
- Signal-based knowledge extraction
- DIKW pyramid categorization (Data, Information, Knowledge, Wisdom)
- Version control with diff tracking
- Implementation plan generation
- Code locker system for file changes

## Relationship Structure

Meeting-Document Relationships:
- Bi-directional linking between meetings and related documents
- Temporal relationship tracking
- Signal inheritance and merging
- Context preservation across entities
- Knowledge graph integration points

Meeting-Signal Relationships:
- One-to-many signal extraction
- Category-based signal organization
- Status tracking state machine
- Approval workflow states
- Signal validation system

Document-Signal Relationships:
- Structured knowledge extraction
- Implementation tracking
- Version-controlled changes
- File relationship mapping
- Code progress metrics

